        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Reading the issue and related ones, I think there is a case to be made for a generalization through the concept of \"contexts\", or at least by taking into account the nesting (and as such, the plurality) of root markers for a buffer:\n\nIn the case of a \"monorepo\" setup like shown just above:\n\n```\nproject/  <- \"super-project\" root\n├── .git/ <- root marker\n├── apps/ <- cwd (but not a project root)\n│   ├── backend/   <- project root\n│   │   ├── package.json  <- root marker\n│   │   └── …\n│   └── frontend/  <- project root\n│       ├── package.json  <- root marker\n│       └── …\n├── libs/\n│   ├── common/ <- project root\n│   │   ├── package.json  <- root marker\n│   │   └── …\n│   └── frobulator/ <- project root\n│       ├── package.json  <- root marker\n│       └── …\n```\n\nThere are several different \"contexts\" in which a command might operate (I'm using \"command\" as a generic operation):\n\n- The `cwd`, which starts where neovim was launched, but which can change with the `:Xcd` family\n- but also project locations, which are independent of \"where\" neovim currently is:\n  - The `backend` project root\n  - The `frontend` project root\n  - maybe the root of the repo can be seen as a project itself, or maybe its own special kind\n\nSo it's not just a binary \"the `cwd` or the project root\", because there could be multiple nested project roots.\n\nLet's say I started neovim on my shell while in the `apps` folder, and I'm currently editing `apps/frontend/foo.js`.\n\nIn this situation, there are two kinds of commands where the \"context\" plays a role:\n\n- Commands that target a buffer, to be interpreted in the scope of a context. Examples could be:\n  - Find all occurences of the word under the cursor (could be scoped to `cwd`, or could be scoped to the inner project root where the file is located, or could be scoped to the whole repo)\n  - Use the LSP rename action on a variable (scoped to the inner project root)\n\n- Commands that target a context in its entirety, like:\n  - Find all occurences of \"frobulon\" in that context\n  - Get all LSP workspace diagnostics for that context\n\n\nTwo separate problems then:\n\n### how are contexts discovered?\n\nBesides the `cwd`, there is the way LSP currently does it, which is looking at root markers when opening a file (I never liked the necessity to open a file to start the LSP, but that's a rant besides the point), but we could imagine other ways (e.g. a plugin on startup that looked for `.git` for a \"root of the repo\" context, or even more dynamic ways)\n\n### How do we specify the context when running a command?\n\nThat's the part where I feel current approaches are lacking.\n\nFor commands targeting a buffer, it's either commands that predate this idea of root markers and always use `cwd`, or commands that only select the innermost project root (which mostly makes sense for LSP actions, but not always, and not necessarily for plugin commands who need this `root_markers` feature. Of course, there *are* commands that only make sense in the innermost context). \n\nFor commands that are context-wide, with the current proposal, as I understand it the only way to express a context other than `cwd`  would be to tie it via a buffer to get it's root_markers, and again it would only work for the innermost context. So no \"search for frobulon in the entire repo\".\n\nThere are things I still can't express without cd'ing around, and it'd be a shame if the resolution of this issue didn't address this use case.\n\nMaybe we could have an API to register and query known contexts, optionally filtered for ones relevant to a buffer? That way LSP becomes just a provider/consumer of this API, plugin authors can also make use of it, and we can even imagine a plugin that wraps legacy \"cwd only\" commands by cd'ing before and after.\n\nThat turned out to be a bit more rambly than I anticipated, sorry! But I hope the rambling was of some use to the discussion.\n\nCheers,",
